# Vercel Web Analytics Implementation

## Summary
Successfully implemented Vercel Web Analytics for this static HTML5 website by adding the official analytics script tags to the index.html file.

## Changes Made

### Modified Files
- **ironside-site/index.html**: Added Vercel Web Analytics script tags in the `<head>` section

### Implementation Details
Since this is a static HTML5 website without a build process or package.json, I followed the official Vercel documentation for HTML5 projects:

1. **Fetched Latest Documentation**: Retrieved the most up-to-date installation instructions from https://vercel.com/docs/analytics/quickstart
2. **Added Analytics Scripts**: Inserted two script tags in the `<head>` section:
   - First script initializes the analytics queue (`window.va`)
   - Second script loads the tracking script from Vercel's CDN (`/_vercel/insights/script.js`)
3. **Placement**: Scripts were added right after the Twitter meta tags and before the `<style>` section for optimal loading

## Why This Approach
- For static HTML sites on Vercel, the `@vercel/analytics` npm package is **not required**
- Vercel automatically serves the analytics script at `/_vercel/insights/script.js` when Web Analytics is enabled
- No package installation or build process needed for static HTML projects
- The script path `/_vercel/insights/script.js` is the standard path used by Vercel for static sites

## Next Steps
To complete the setup:
1. Deploy this change to Vercel
2. Enable Web Analytics in the Vercel project dashboard (Settings → Analytics)
3. Analytics will start tracking page views automatically once enabled
4. View analytics data in the Vercel dashboard after deployment

## Notes
- The implementation follows Vercel's official documentation exactly
- No dependencies or package managers were needed for this static site
- The analytics script loads asynchronously (using `defer`) to avoid blocking page rendering
- Analytics will only be active after deployment to Vercel and enabling the feature in the dashboard
